[
    {
        "content": "<p>I wrote a blog article on Galois connections:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2023/04/bargainbasement_mathematics.html\">Bargain-basement mathematics</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"428716\">@Jean-Baptiste Vienney</span> might like my treatment of the Nullstellensatz.... even though I don't even state the Nullstellensatz, just an easier theorem!</p>",
        "id": 351172462,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1681949217
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you! This is exactly the stuff I wanted to understand after you told me about the Nullstellensatz as an adjunction.</p>",
        "id": 351172848,
        "sender_full_name": "Jean-Baptiste Vienney",
        "timestamp": 1681949549
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Good!  The basic idea is really simple.  Then people make it harder.</p>",
        "id": 351172894,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1681949594
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I wanted to understand the list of Galois connections given by <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"414434\">@Martin Brandenburg</span> <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/1249883/how-is-the-notion-of-adjunction-of-two-functors-usefull\">here</a></p>",
        "id": 351173231,
        "sender_full_name": "Jean-Baptiste Vienney",
        "timestamp": 1681949886
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I will be super happy if I understand all of them, so much space saved in my memory if I understand all of that under a same schema.</p>",
        "id": 351173308,
        "sender_full_name": "Jean-Baptiste Vienney",
        "timestamp": 1681949979
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nice!  I think I know what all those are except \"Grothendieck's main theorem of Galois theory\".   I might know what that is if someone reminds me....</p>",
        "id": 351173311,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1681949985
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A bunch of them are really best thought of as contravariant adjunctions between interesting <em>categories</em>, while some are contravariant adjunctions between mere posets.</p>",
        "id": 351173405,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1681950053
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Furthermore, 3 of them are dualities between commutative rings and spaces, where we get a commutative ring on a space from looking at ring-valued functions on that space.   2 of them are dualities between abelian groups of some kind and abelian groups of the same kind, obtained by homming the group into the circle group.  And 2 are dualities between 'covering spaces' and their groups of deck transformations.</p>",
        "id": 351173637,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1681950267
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So I'd say there are at most 3 basic ideas kinds of Galois connections listed here... each of which can be worked out in many different ways.</p>",
        "id": 351173675,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1681950316
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If I ever write my book <em>Learning Math With Categories</em>, I should remember this.</p>",
        "id": 351173747,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1681950375
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Looks very interesting! I'll have to come back to this article on a day when I don't have a headache. Among other things, it looks like this article relates to my ongoing quest to understand adjoint functors...</p>\n<p>Well, I had fun understanding a proof of this (from the article):<br>\n\"On these new smaller versions of the sets X and Y, the maps L and R become inverses! You can prove this simply by fiddling around with the definition of Galois connection. If you’ve never done it before, it takes some thought. \"<br>\nI tried to prove this on my own, but I eventually had to resort to the nlab. The proof there was a lot simpler than I had expected!</p>",
        "id": 351181823,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1681958544
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think what is meant by Grothendieck's Galois theory is the pi_1 version of reconstructing a group from a fibre functor, but here having one valued in sets, not in vector spaces</p>",
        "id": 351204386,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1681964861
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277503\">@David Egolf</span> wrote:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I tried to prove this on my own, but I eventually had to resort to the nLab. The proof there was a lot simpler than I had expected!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yeah, you just have to fiddle with the definitions, but it seems sneaky at first.  It helps a lot if you've been told that given order preserving maps </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mspace width=\"1em\"/><mi>R</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> L : X \\to Y,  \\quad R : Y \\to X </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:1em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>with </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≤</mo><mi>y</mi><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟺</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> L(x) \\le y \\iff x \\le R(y) </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7194em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⟺</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>we always have</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>R</mi><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> x \\le RL(x) </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> </p>\n<p>for all <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\in X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi>R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≤</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> LR(y) \\le y </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>for all <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y \\in Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7335em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>.  These foreshadow important facts about adjoint functors, so they're worth remembering!  And you can use these to show what we want now, namely</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi>R</mi><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> LRL(x) = L(x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> </p>\n<p>and </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mi>L</mi><mi>R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> RLR(y) = R(y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></p>",
